title: Apple Boutique
description: The Apple Boutique was a retail store, located at 94 Baker Street, and one of the first business ventures made by The Beatles' fledgling Apple Corps. Opened on December 7, 1967 (with John Lennon and George Harrison attending the grand opening), the Apple Boutique's primary advertisement was an elaborate mural, painted on one whole outside wall of their location, designed by Dutch artistic trio The Fool, facing out into Baker Street. Inside the shop, clothing and accessories also designed (or handpicked) by The Fool were available. Almost immediately, trouble broke out as other local businesses objected to the psychedelically-painted wall while indoors, shoplifting became the number one pastime. Would-be customers began helping themselves to the trendy items. The Fool's members also made a habit of taking their choice of the merchandise. The boutique soon began losing money at an alarming rate. Ultimately, the local businesses won, with the mural removed by civic order. Inside, after months of steady losses, it was decided to close the boutique. This happened on July 30, 1968. The Beatles, their wives and their girlfriends came the night before, to take what they wanted; then, the next morning, it was announced that all remaining stock was to be given away for free. The store was empty within hours, the public (numbering in the hundreds) nearly rioting to get their share.
